{"id":"2305.08134","submitter":"Emel G\\\"urb\\\"uz","authors":"Emel G\\\"urb\\\"uz and Biplab Sanyal","title":"Systematic study of amorphous 2D graphene, silicene and silicon carbide:\n  Investigation of structural, electronic, optical and vibrational properties","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.mtrl-sci","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Although 2D solids and their vdW heterostructures have garnered much\nattention recently, their amorphous forms have been less explored. We present a\ndetailed analysis of the structural, electronic, and thermal properties of 2D\namorphous graphene (A-Gra), silicene (A-Si), and silicon carbide (A-SiC) using\nClassical Molecular Dynamics (MD) simulations and first-principles\ncalculations. Our results showed that A-Gra is planar at 0 K and wrinkled at\n300 K, like its crystalline counterpart. At both temperatures, it can form\nstable vdW solids while maintaining metallic behavior. We also demonstrate that\nA-Si creates covalent bonds in layered structures while keeping its\nmetallicity. Its optical spectrum is blue-shifted in parallel polarization\nrelative to crystalline silicene, and its plasmon peak is in the UV range with\nsix-times higher intensity. Furthermore, we show that 2D silicon carbide can be\nstabilized as a single layer or in layered structures with bonding between Si\natoms only. A-SiC's plasmon peak is in the UV range. All three structures'\noptical spectra are observed as red-shifted compared to their crystalline\ncounterparts, and their absorption spectra range from IR to UV. Their common\nheat carriers are extendons, especially diffusions, and their thermal\nconductivity is calculated to be lower than that of their crystalline\ncounterparts. Our findings suggest that the uneven charge distributions around\nlocal ring structures in all three systems can be exploited in future\nelectronic, thermo-electric, and opto-electronic devices with local\nfunctionality.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sun, 14 May 2023 12:03:37 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-05-16"}
